{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:06:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:06:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15133"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15133"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.26,0.29,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100864"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7821"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83286"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"10521"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33422"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100864"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old non-pregnant woman presents with symptoms of uncomplicated urinary tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be offered first-line to a non-immunocompromised, non-pregnant adult woman for treatment of uncomplicated acute cystitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Symptomatic treatment only","Nitrofurantoin","Trimethoprim","Amoxicillin with clavulanic acid","Ciprofloxacin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor non-pregnant, non-immunocompromised adult women with uncomplicated cystitis, \u003Cstrong\u003Esymptomatic treatment only\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended as first-line. Many women recover without antibiotics within one week, and the risk of complications is low. Antibiotics may reduce symptom duration but are associated with adverse effects, increased antimicrobial resistance, and disruption of the gut microbiome which can result in life-threatening \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitrofurantoin\u003C/strong\u003E is a first-line antibiotic if antibiotics are required, but symptomatic management alone is preferred initially. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is now second-line due to resistance rates among \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E in Australian isolates increasing, now being above 20%. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin with clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E should not be used unless no appropriate alternative exists due to its broad spectrum activity and higher risk of side effects, including \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E and other fluoroquinolones are reserved for resistant cases to help prevent antimicrobial resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibiotic choice, if needed, should be guided by local resistance patterns and patient factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line management of uncomplicated cystitis in non-pregnant, non-immunocompromised adult women may be symptomatic treatment alone.","Nitrofurantoin is a first-line antibiotic for acute cystitis if antibiotics are required.","Trimethoprim is now considered second-line due to increasing resistance.","Amoxicillin with clavulanic acid and ciprofloxacin are not recommended as first-line due to resistance and side effect concerns."],"references":["Colgan R, Williams M. Diagnosis and treatment of acute uncomplicated cystitis. Am Fam Physician. 2011 Oct 1;84(7):771-6. PMID: 22010614.","Patel P, Wermuth HR, Calhoun C, et al. Antibiotics. [Updated 2023 May 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535443/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Therapeutic Guidelines. Acute cystitis in adults [Internet]. Therapeutic Guidelines. 2025. Available from: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.eu1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=bartonella-infections\u0026guidelinename=auto\u0026sectionId=c_ABG_Acute-cystitis-in-adults_topic_7#c_ABG_Acute-cystitis-in-adults_topic_7"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83286"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15133"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83286"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-27T18:04:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-27T18:04:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7821"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100864"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14"